  "prompt": "What's the difference between science, engineering and technology?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the differences between science, engineering, and technology:\n\nScience:\n- Focuses on understanding natural phenomena\n- Seeks knowledge and explanations about the world\n- Uses observation, hypothesis, experimentation, and theory\n- Aims to discover how things work\n- Examples: Biology, Physics, Chemistry\n\nEngineering:\n- Applies scientific and mathematical principles to solve practical problems\n- Designs and creates solutions, systems, and structures\n- Develops processes and methods to meet specific needs\n- Transforms scientific knowledge into practical applications\n- Examples: Mechanical engineering, electrical engineering, civil engineering\n\nTechnology:\n- The practical application of scientific and engineering knowledge\n- Tools, machines, techniques, and systems created to solve problems\n- Focuses on creating products and processes\n- Translates engineering designs into tangible solutions\n- Examples: Smartphones, computers, medical devices\n\nRelationship:\n- Science provides the foundational knowledge\n- Engineering applies that knowledge to design solutions\n- Technology represents the practical implementation of those solutions\n\nIn essence:\n- Science asks \"How does it work?\"\n- Engineering asks \"How can we use this knowledge?\"\n- Technology says \"Here's a practical solution\"\n\nThese fields are interconnected and often work together to advance human understanding and capabilities.",
